-- Sensex Declines for Second Day as NTPC, Tech Mahindra Post Lower Earnings
-- B y   R a j h k u m a r   K   S h a a w   a n d   R u c h i k a   T u l s h y a n
-- 2010-10-27T10:56:11Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-10-27/sensex-declines-for-second-day-as-ntpc-tech-mahindra-post-lower-earnings.html
Indian stocks fell, driving the
benchmark index to a one-week low, as financial reports by
companies including  NTPC Ltd.  and Asian Paints Ltd. prompted
concern profit growth will slow.  NTPC, the nation’s largest power producer, dropped the most
in five months after profit sank for the third quarter in a row.
 Tech Mahindra Ltd.  declined for the first time in five days
after its net income fell more than analysts expected. Asian
Paints slid the most in 10 months after posting a 21 percent
profit tumble, while telecom shares extended yesterday’s retreat
as  Idea Cellular Ltd. ’s earnings shrank 18 percent.  “The markets are taking their cue from earnings,” said
 Gopal Agrawal , head of equities at Mirae Asset Financial group
in Mumbai, which has $2.5 billion invested in India. The results
are “muted in utilities and telecoms. We have reduced exposure
on consumer discretionary stocks,” Agrawal said, declining to
comment on specific shares.  The Bombay Stock Exchange’s  Sensitive Index , or  Sensex ,
lost 216.02, or 1.1 percent, to 20,005.37 as of the 3:30 p.m.
close in Mumbai, the lowest since Oct. 20. The S&P CNX  Nifty 
Index on the National Stock Exchange dropped 1.1 percent to
6,012.65. The  BSE 200 Index  retreated 0.9 percent to 2,550.97.  NTPC lost 3.4 percent to 198.25 rupees, its biggest slide
since May 21. Its net income in the three months ended Sept. 30
fell 2 percent to 21.1 billion ($475 million) rupees from a year
earlier as expenditure outpaced sales growth.  Tech Mahindra decreased 2 percent to 770.75 rupees as net
income fell to 1.51 billion rupees in the September quarter
after accounting for charges related to its acquisition of
Satyam Computer Services Ltd., less than the 1.66 billion rupee
average of 18 analyst estimates compiled by Bloomberg.  Asian Paints  Asian Paints sank 3.5 percent to 2,502.6 rupees, its
biggest drop since Dec. 21, after saying second-quarter profit
fell to 1.96 billion rupees from 2.54 billion rupees a year
earlier.  Idea Cellular, the third-largest mobile-phone company by
value, slid 3.2 percent to 67.25 rupees, extending its 3 percent
retreat yesterday. It larger peer  Bharti Airtel Ltd.  declined
2.1 percent to 321.95 rupees, its lowest level since Oct. 20.  Gujarat Alkalies & Chemicals Ltd. , a maker of caustic soda,
declined 6.3 percent to 133.45 rupees after its second-quarter
profit fell 31 percent to 201.2 million rupees.  “The mood is subdued among investors today,” said  Alex Mathews , head of research at Geojit BNP Paribas Financial
Services Ltd. in Kochi. “Some of the earnings have
disappointed.”  Union Bank of India , a state-run lender, sank 6 percent to
392.9 rupees after its September quarter profit dropped 40
percent.  Gyscoal Alloys Ltd. , the manufacturer of stainless steel,
surged 15 percent to 81.65 rupees in its debut trading today,
while  Prestige Estates Projects Ltd. , the developer in a mall
venture with CapitaMalls Asia Ltd., gained 5.6 percent to 193.15
rupees in its first day of trading.  To contact the reporter on this story:
